{"actual_usd":0.15686,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":237,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"Same Jesus, truly — but not merely back the way Lazarus was back.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching on the edge of my Bible.* \"The scars matter. He tells Thomas to touch them. So it is the crucified body, not a replacement body. But it is also glorified — raised in a new mode of life, no longer subject to death.\"\n\n*I lift one hand a little, sorting the thought as the square stays quiet around us.* \"That helps with the recognition question. It wasn't that he was a different person. It was that resurrection had changed him into the fullness of what that same body was now for. Sometimes their eyes were opened to know him; sometimes grief, shock, or God's own timing seemed to veil it. Mary thinks he's the gardener till he says her name. The men on the road walk with him awhile before they know him. Then — suddenly — they do.\"\n\n\"So I'd say: same body, yes; same wounds, yes; but glorified, deathless, and changed enough that recognition was not always immediate. Not a swap. A victory.\"","rolling_24h_usd":86.964585,"run_id":"7e4d4017-60ca-4470-8d96-9cc462c17142"}
